THIS IS A LONG ONE 😅🤍

Next month I’ll be celebrating 8 years in corporate America. Whew, what a ride it has been! My first job was at a major manufacturing company in an extremely rural town. It was an accelerated rotational program and I really feel like it set me up for a quick trajectory. It wasn't diverse, and honestly was the precipice for why I started Corporate Curly.

I really wish I would have vlogged throughout those years, because I've been afforded some beautiful opportunities. I was able to live in multiple states (expenses fully paid by companies), travel, gain new experiences, meet new people, and learn a lot! it's really been a blessing throughout the years. But moving upward has definitely come with its highs and lows. I am Nigerian though, Igbo to be exact, and we don't give up. 😆🇳🇬

If I could look back on those years I’d share 3 lessons :

1. They never lied when they said your network is your net worth. Cultivate genuine, meaningful relationships. ALL the time, at all times. You just never know how you could benefit each other in the future.

2. Seek out those opportunities that could help give you exposure and stretch you in ways that make you uncomfortable. Those are the periods where you will actually challenge yourself to grow the most.

3. As black women, we really do experience challenges simply bc of who we are. Seek out your support group, mentors, people who could help you through your journey. Find an organization where you are valued and find your tribe there. And if you aren’t protect your mental health and find some where that will honor your value. 

When you look back on the history of Corporate America, these spaces truly were not created for us. However, I do believe that if you find the right people in the right environment, the impact we can make is immense and we can truly thrive. 🙏🏾🤍

I started Corporate Curly simply because I wanted other women to understand that the hair that naturally grows out of their head is absolutely professional. And I wanted to create content and imagery that amplifies that message. 

I really could have never imagined the beautiful journey and community that would manifest since I began six years ago. I will forever be grateful 🥹🫶🏾. 

I’m not where I want to be by any means, but I am so excited for the journey. 

I recently applied for the #sephorasquad bc I want to continue to push myself outside of my comfort zone 😅 and if it’s a way to continue to share the message that #naturalhairisprofessional then I am so here for it! 

Thank you to everyone who has left a testimonial, I truly appreciate your kind words. I’ll leave the link in my stories for anyone who would like to leave a message🫶🏾😘

I posted a story about this topic last week. Interesting to see so many people agree with this. SO CAN YOUR PROFESSIONAL STYLE GET YOU PROMOTED? What do you think?!

I say, it can help. Your professional style can contribute to how others perceive you in the workplace, and it may influence your chances of getting promoted. Putting effort into how you dress for your workplace shows that you put thought into your attire and some people may perceive that as you taking your role “seriously” and can enhance your professional image. Consider the following tips:

1. **Dress for the job you want:** this has been said time and time again. 

2. **Read the Room when it comes to dress code:** Observe the dress habits of colleagues and supervisors. Adapting your style to the company culture can help you gain some tips on what’s “typical” at a company. 

3. **Express Your Personal Brand:** Find ways to incorporate your personal style. This can help you stand out and be memorable.

4. **Dress for Your Goals:** Consider how you want to be perceived in your desired role. Dressing in a way that aligns with your career goals can signal to others that you are intentional with your professional appearance.

While professional style is just one aspect of career advancement, it can contribute to creating a positive and confident professional presence. Make sure you put as much and even more effort into your skills, achievements, and overall work performance for a well-rounded approach to career growth.

I work hard bc I’m driven. But I work even harder because now that I’m an adult, like a real real adult. All bills paid on my own lol. I realize how hard coming to an unknown country without much could have been. The struggles that my parents went through mean so much more now. I am so grateful that my parents can sit back and watch the fruit of their labor thrive and grow. And I’m even more grateful that in this chapter of life, we can spoil them now.

My dad visiting me in Chicago these past two weeks has been such a pleasure. While working and living alone in this phase of life I can get so consumed in that, that I always try to make it a priority to show up and prioritize time with my loved ones when I can.
